social_posts.post_text:
Our soul, Marcus Aurelius wrote, is dyed by the color of our thoughts. 

Perspective is everything. So choose it wisely. Know that you have that power. 🧠

Hittin’ the road, and the shutter. 📸 ✈️

This past week: TX ➡️ OR ➡️ NY ➡️ TX

This time of year is about rebirth, discovery, and opportunity. I’ve been in cruise mode for the past five months and only lifting weights once a week. While I’m grateful for my work over the past few years that built the framework and metabolism to support such a break, it’s time to rengage with the gym. This doesn’t mean a hard pivot to daily lifting - small intentional changes that accumulate overtime is the true pathway to success. Spring is a few days away, start thinking about where your first small change can happen. 🐣💪🏼

location.city_name: Grove of Titans, Redwood National Forest

social_posts.post_text:
There is magic in the forest, and wisdom in the ancient redwoods. With trees alive since the Roman Empire and standing well over 300 feet tall, the Grove of Titans is obviously the ideal garden of growth. Planting myself in the grove and watering my thoughts with the sounds of the woods, was the therapeutic experience I had hoped for. 

As John Muir said “And into the forest I go, to lose my mind and find my soul.” 🌱❤️

A strong cornerstone of my personality is being strongly obsessional, to put it mildly. I pursue my contemporary interests in such extraordinary detail and lengths that I develop tunnel vision. This narrow depth of field has been quite rewarding in many ways, but I have also found it to be a double-edged sword. Tunnel vision kills creativity.

Creativity often requires the ability to broaden one’s perspectives and dive into the peripheral. While there is an abundance of knowledge to be had in the center, I’ve found the real treasures are scattered just out of view. Never be afraid to adjust your lens. 🔍
“We all want to break our orbits, float like a satellite gone wild in space, run the risk of disintegration. We all want to take our lives in our own hands and hurl them out among the stars.” ✨
“There is no easy way. There is only hard work, late nights, early mornings, practice, rehearsal, repetition, study, sweat, blood, toil, frustration, and discipline.” 💯

social_posts.post_text:
In recent years my focus for self improvement shifted from the physical to the emotional. I dove head first into the introspective abyss with the deep desire to really understand what makes me tick. I found the study to be immensely satisfying, but for other reasons than internal understanding. The trailhead was perhaps selfish, but the path ended with a profoundly expanded level of empathy. When we find ourselves in a place of misalignment with the people in our lives, we are inherently terrible at trying to see the world through their eyes. This still doesn’t come natural, but I hit pause in those moments and try to manifest their lens. 

Finding myself, helped me find others. As Carl Jung puts it, “Knowing your own darkness is the best method for dealing with the darknesses of other people.”

The allure of an unfamiliar place is intoxicating. Venturing through the lively streets of Shinjuku in Tokyo, I'm enveloped in a symphony of sights and sounds. Neon lights dance around me as I weave my way through crowds, snippets of conversation floating by in a language I strain to comprehend. Each corner turned reveals a new discovery, from tiny alleyway izakayas to sensory explosions of color and movement. I have no destination, no agenda, no plan.

I'm simply present, soaking up each moment, embracing the joy of being beautifully lost in this labyrinth of exploration. My senses feel renewed, alive, as if I'm seeing the world clearly for the first time. No map could ever encapsulate the magic found in veering off the beaten path, wandering wide-eyed with childlike curiosity. Here, fully immersed in the unfamiliar, I'm reminded that sometimes it's in being lost that we find ourselves. Where will I wander tomorrow?

"Not all those who wander are lost." - J.R.R. Tolkien

Wandering the ancient streets of Kyoto is a walk through time, where tradition collides seamlessly with modernity. 

I lose myself in the labyrinth of market alleys, stumbling upon quiet corners that transport me back centuries - vermilion shrines guarded by noble komainu, mossy statues standing watch in tranquil gardens, stone foxes keeping vigil over Inari's blessings.

Turn a corner and I'm met with everyday scenes - young women gracefully dressed in kimono, locals gathering at neighborhood bars, and the innate friendliness and hospitality of the people. Through my lens I try to capture the essence of this sacred city, its effortless dance between past and present.

In the shadows of towering pagodas, beneath the bows of thousand-year-old trees, one feels the heritage that permeates each step here. Kyoto's enduring spirituality breathes life into every detail.

I bow my head at yet another modest shrine, pausing to take in the profound heritage surrounding me, knowing I've only just scratched the surface of the wonders this city holds.

There will always be another rep, another mile, another skill to refine. We all have more growing to do. But just like the peony, the most vibrant colors come from pushing through the soil. One petal, one workout at a time, we can get there. 🌺💪🏼
